.SH NAME
Bitcoin::Crypto::Util \- General Bitcoin utilities
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 10
\&        use Bitcoin::Crypto::Util qw(
\&                validate_wif
\&                validate_segwit
\&                get_address_type
\&                get_key_type
\&                get_public_key_compressed
\&                generate_mnemonic
\&                mnemonic_from_entropy
\&                mnemonic_to_seed
\&                get_path_info
\&                from_format
\&                to_format
\&                pack_compactsize
\&                unpack_compactsize
\&                hash160
\&                hash256
\&                merkle_root
\&                tagged_hash
\&                lift_x
\&                has_even_y
\&                get_taproot_ext
\&        );
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
These are basic utilities for working with Bitcoin. They do not fit well as a
part of other, more specialized packages.
.SH FUNCTIONS
.IX Header "FUNCTIONS"
.SS validate_wif
.IX Subsection "validate_wif"
.Vb 1
\&        $is_wif = validate_wif($wif)
.Ve
.PP
Ensures Base58 encoded string looks like encoded private key in WIF format.
Throws an exception if \f(CW$wif\fR is not valid base58.
.PP
This method accepts a secret argument. See Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret for details.
.SS validate_segwit
.IX Subsection "validate_segwit"
.Vb 1
\&        $segwit_version = validate_segwit($program)
.Ve
.PP
Performs a segwit program validation on \f(CW$program\fR, which is expected to be a
byte string in which the first byte is a segwit version.
.PP
The function returns the detected segwit program version. Note that it does not
perform any more checks than ensuring the byte string is in correct format.
.PP
The current implementation is in line with validations for segwit versions \f(CW0\fR
and \f(CW1\fR. Future segwit version addresses will work just fine, but no special
validation will be performed until implemented.
.PP
Raises an exception (\f(CW\*(C`Bitcoin::Crypto::Exception::SegwitProgram\*(C'\fR) on error.
Returns the detected segwit program version.
.SS get_address_type
.IX Subsection "get_address_type"
.Vb 1
\&        $type = get_address_type($address, $network = Bitcoin::Crypto::Network\->get)
.Ve
.PP
Tries to guess the type of \f(CW$address\fR. Returns \f(CW\*(C`P2PKH\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`P2SH\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`P2WPKH\*(C'\fR,
\&\f(CW\*(C`P2WSH\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`P2TR\*(C'\fR. May throw Base58, Bech32, SegwitProgram, Address or other
exceptions if the string is not a valid address.
.SS get_key_type
.IX Subsection "get_key_type"
.Vb 1
\&        $is_private = get_key_type($bytestr);
.Ve
.PP
Checks if the \f(CW$bytestr\fR looks like a valid ASN X9.62 format (compressed /
uncompressed / hybrid public key or private key entropy up to curve size bits).
.PP
Returns boolean which states whether the key is private. Returns
undef if \f(CW$bytestr\fR does not look like a valid key entropy.
.SS get_public_key_compressed
.IX Subsection "get_public_key_compressed"
.Vb 1
\&        $is_compressed = get_public_key_compressed($bytestr);
.Ve
.PP
Checks if the \f(CW$bytestr\fR looks like a valid ASN X9.62 format (compressed /
uncompressed / hybrid public key).
.PP
Returns boolean which states whether the key is compressed. Returns
undef if \f(CW$bytestr\fR does not look like a valid public key.
.SS generate_mnemonic
.IX Subsection "generate_mnemonic"
.Vb 1
\&        $mnemonic = generate_mnemonic($len = 128, $lang = \*(Aqen\*(Aq)
.Ve
.PP
Generates a new mnemonic code using Bytes::Random::Secure. Default entropy
is \f(CW128\fR bits. This can be increased up to \f(CW256\fR bits (increasing by \f(CW32\fR
bits each step) with \f(CW$len\fR argument.
.PP
Other languages than english require installation of additional modules
language\-specific for Bitcoin::BIP39.
.PP
Returns newly generated BIP39 mnemonic string. Dies when \f(CW$len\fR is invalid
(less than \f(CW128\fR, more than \f(CW256\fR or not divisible by \f(CW32\fR).
.PP
In some environments a problem may be encountered that causes the secure random
bytes generator to block the program execution (See
"BLOCKING ENTROPY SOURCE" in Bytes::Random::Secure). In this case you can use
"mnemonic_from_entropy" and pass in entropy generated by
Bytes::Random::Secure in non\-blocking mode (via the OO interface).
.SS mnemonic_from_entropy
.IX Subsection "mnemonic_from_entropy"
.Vb 1
\&        $mnemonic = mnemonic_from_entropy($entropy, $lang = \*(Aqen\*(Aq)
.Ve
.PP
Generates a new mnemonic code from custom entropy given in \f(CW$entropy\fR (a
bytestring). This entropy should be of the same bit size as in
"generate_mnemonic". Returns newly generated BIP39 mnemonic string.
.PP
This can be useful to avoid relying on the underlying PRNG implementation used
by Bitcoin::BIP39.
.PP
Another use would be implementing one\*(Aqs own entropy source that can be truly
random, not just cryptographically\-secure. A popular example would be capturing
user\*(Aqs mouse movements.
.PP
Be aware that the method you use to generate a mnemonic will be a very
important factor in your key\*(Aqs security. If possible, use real sources of
randomness (not pseudo\-random) or a cryptographically secure pseduo\-random
number generator like the one used by Bytes::Random::Secure.
.PP
This method accepts a secret argument. See Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret for details.
.SS mnemonic_to_seed
.IX Subsection "mnemonic_to_seed"
.Vb 1
\&        $seed = mnemonic_to_seed($mnemonic, $password = undef);
.Ve
.PP
Transforms the given BIP39 \f(CW$mnemonic\fR and an optional \f(CW$password\fR into a
valid BIP32 \f(CW$seed\fR, which can be fed into
"from_seed" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::ExtPrivate.
.PP
\&\f(CW$seed\fR is a \f(CW512\fR bit bytestring (64 characters). \f(CW$mnemonic\fR should be a
BIP39 mnemonic, but will not be checked against a dictionary.
.PP
This function is only useful if you need a seed instead of mnemonic (for
example, you use a wallet implementation which does not implement BIP39). If
you only want to create a private key from mnemonic, you should consider using
"from_mnemonic" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::ExtPrivate instead.
.PP
\&\fBImportant note about unicode:\fR this function only accepts UTF8\-decoded
strings (both \f(CW$mnemonic\fR and \f(CW$password\fR), but can\*(Aqt detect whether it got
it or not. This will only become a problem if you use non\-ascii mnemonic and/or
password. If there\*(Aqs a possibility of non\-ascii, always use utf8 and set
binmodes to get decoded (wide) characters to avoid problems recovering your
wallet.
.PP
This method accepts a secret argument. See Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret for details.
.SS get_path_info
.IX Subsection "get_path_info"
.Vb 1
\&        $path_data = get_path_info($path);
.Ve
.PP
Tries to get derivation path data from \f(CW$path\fR, which can be a string like
\&\f(CW"m/1/3\*(Aq"\fR or an object which implements \f(CW\*(C`get_derivation_path\*(C'\fR method (and
does \f(CW\*(C`Bitcoin::Crypto::Role::WithDerivationPath\*(C'\fR). Returns undef if \f(CW$path\fR
is not a valid path, otherwise returns the structure as an instance of
Bitcoin::Crypto::DerivationPath:
.PP
.Vb 7
\&        {
\&                private => bool, # is path derivation private (lowercase m)
\&                path => [
\&                        # derivation path with 2^31 added to every hardened child number
\&                        int, int, ..
\&                ],
\&        }
.Ve
.PP
You may also use "DerivationPath" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Types type and its
coercions to achieve the same effect (but with an exception instead of undef on
failure).
.SS to_format
.IX Subsection "to_format"
.Vb 1
\&        $encoded = to_format [$format => $bytes];
.Ve
.PP
Unpacks bytestring \f(CW$bytes\fR into the given \f(CW$format\fR. Use this to avoid
manual unpacking.
.PP
Supported \f(CW$format\fR values are:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`bytes\*(C'\fR, does nothing
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`hex\*(C'\fR, encodes as a hexadecimal string (no \f(CW\*(C`0x\*(C'\fR prefix)
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`base58\*(C'\fR, uses base58 and includes the checksum (base58check)
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`base64\*(C'\fR, uses base64
.SS from_format
.IX Subsection "from_format"
.Vb 1
\&        $decoded = from_format [$format => $string]
.Ve
.PP
Reverse of "to_format" \- decodes \f(CW$string\fR into bytestring, treating it as
\&\f(CW$format\fR.
.PP
\&\fINote: this is not usually needed to be called explicitly, as every bytestring
parameter of the module will do this conversion implicitly.\fR
.SS pack_compactsize
.IX Subsection "pack_compactsize"
.Vb 1
\&        $bytestr = pack_compactsize($integer)
.Ve
.PP
Serializes \f(CW$integer\fR as Bitcoin\*(Aqs CompactSize format and returns it as a byte string.
.SS unpack_compactsize
.IX Subsection "unpack_compactsize"
.Vb 1
\&        $integer = unpack_compactsize($bytestr, $pos = undef)
.Ve
.PP
Deserializes CompactSize from \f(CW$bytestr\fR, returning an integer.
.PP
If \f(CW$pos\fR is passed, it must be a reference to a scalar containing the
position at which to start the decoding. It will be modified to contain the
next position after the CompactSize. If not, decoding will start at 0 and will raise
an exception if \f(CW$bytestr\fR contains anything other than CompactSize.
.SS hash160
.IX Subsection "hash160"
.Vb 1
\&        $hash = hash160($data)
.Ve
.PP
This is hash160 used by Bitcoin (\f(CW\*(C`RIPEMD160\*(C'\fR of \f(CW\*(C`SHA256\*(C'\fR)
.SS hash256
.IX Subsection "hash256"
.Vb 1
\&        $hash = hash256($data)
.Ve
.PP
This is hash256 used by Bitcoin (\f(CW\*(C`SHA256\*(C'\fR of \f(CW\*(C`SHA256\*(C'\fR)
.SS merkle_root
.IX Subsection "merkle_root"
.Vb 1
\&        $hash = merkle_root([$leaf1, $leaf2, ...])
.Ve
.PP
Calculates a merkle root of input array reference. Leaves will be run through a
double SHA256 before calculating the root.
.SS tagged_hash
.IX Subsection "tagged_hash"
.Vb 1
\&        $hash = tagged_hash($tag, $message)
.Ve
.PP
Calculates a tagged hash of \f(CW$message\fR using \f(CW$tag\fR as a tag. These hashes
are described in BIP340.
.PP
\&\fBImportant note about unicode:\fR this function only accepts UTF8\-decoded
strings for \f(CW$tag\fR, but can\*(Aqt detect whether it got it or not. This will only
become a problem if you use non\-ascii tag. If there\*(Aqs a possibility of
non\-ascii, always use utf8 and set binmodes to get decoded (wide) characters.
.SS lift_x
.IX Subsection "lift_x"
.Vb 1
\&        $public_key = lift_x($xonly_public_key)
.Ve
.PP
This implements \f(CW\*(C`lift_x\*(C'\fR function defined in BIP340. Returns a compressed ECC
public key with even Y coordinate as a bytestring for a given 32\-byte bytestring
\&\f(CW$xonly_public_key\fR. Throws an exception if the result is not a valid public
key.
.SS has_even_y
.IX Subsection "has_even_y"
.Vb 1
\&        $even_y = has_even_y($public_key)
.Ve
.PP
This implements \f(CW\*(C`has_even_y\*(C'\fR function defined in BIP340. Returns a boolean for
a given serialized \f(CW$public_key\fR \- a bytestring. Throws an exception if the
argument is not a valid public key.
.SS get_taproot_ext
.IX Subsection "get_taproot_ext"
.Vb 1
\&        $bytestring = get_taproot_ext($ext_flag, %args)
.Ve
.PP
This function generates a binary ext for \f(CW$ext_flag\fR used by taproot
transactions. \f(CW%args\fR and result depend on the value of \f(CW$ext_flag\fR:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`$ext_flag = 0\*(C'\fR
.Sp
\&\f(CW%args\fR are empty, an empty string is generated.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`$ext_flag = 1\*(C'\fR
.Sp
\&\f(CW\*(C`script_tree\*(C'\fR \- instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Script::Tree (required)
.Sp
\&\f(CW\*(C`leaf_id\*(C'\fR \- integer, identifier of \f(CW\*(C`script_tree\*(C'\fR leaf for current context (required)
.Sp
\&\f(CW\*(C`codesep_pos\*(C'\fR \- position of last executed codeseparator, or undef if there was none (optional)
.Sp
Returns ext according to BIP342.
.PP
Raises an exception for unknown \f(CW$ext_flag\fR.
